<author><name><![CDATA[notinasia]]></name></author>
<updated>2010-05-20T16:00:26-07:00</updated>
<published>2010-05-20T16:00:26-07:00</published>
<id>http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6384&amp;p=61666#p61666</id>
<link href="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6384&amp;p=61666#p61666"/>
<title type="html"><![CDATA[Not enough original homebrew games. Need more tools?]]></title>

<content type="html" xml:base="http://forums.nesdev.com/viewtopic.php?t=6384&amp;p=61666#p61666"><![CDATA[
I don't think I've ever seen credits for a console game with just 2 or 3 names (I've never played atari either though).<br /><br />For example, MM1 credits:<br /><br />1 planner<br />4 character designers<br />1 programmer<br />2 sound programmers<br /><br />Granted, people are using a lot more advanced tools now than back in the day, but that's just one person (in his spare time) doing a task that would normally be done by a team (9:00 to 5:00 and getting paid).  I'm not saying it's impossible, it's just pretty inefficient- albeit fun, challenging, etc.  And I think that's why some of the projects around here never get finished.<br /><br />I think a good way to get more homebrew games out would be teamwork.<p>Statistics: Posted by <a href="http://forums.nesdev.com/memberlist.php?mode=viewprofile&amp;u=4148">notinasia</a> — Thu May 20, 2010 4:00 pm</p><hr />
]]></content>
